T J.J. rquez-Ortiz, J.F.S. Lamb, L.D. Johnson, D.K. Barnes and R.E. Stucker, 1999, Heritability of crown traits in alfalfa, Crop Science, Vol 39, Issue 1 pgs. 38-43
T Crown Depth (distance from the soil level to the top of the tap root) - 0.5cm to 5cm
T Crown width (just below the soil surface) - 2cm to 12cm or greater
T Number of crown stems - 2 to 10 or more
T Crown stem width - 2mm to 6mm or greater
T Number of crown buds - none to 12 or more
T
T D.K. Barnes, R.B. Pearce, G.E. Carlson, R.H. Hart, and C.H. Hanson. 1969. SPecific Leaf Weight Differences in Alfalfa Associated with Variety and
T Plant Age. Crop Science, Vol 9, pgs. 421-423.
T Values of Specific leaf weight measured in the paper varied from 2.15 to 4.3, with early season growth mostly in the area of 2.15 to 2.72 mg/cm^2
T Conversion to m^2/kg is * 10^6 mg/kg * 10^-4 m^2/cm^2 = 100 / mg/cm^2
T
T 2.15 mg/cm^2 = 100 / 2.15 m^2/kg = 46.5 m^2/kg, 100 / 2.72 = 36.8, 100 / 4.3 = 23.3
T
T M. H. Hall, C. J. Nelson, J. H. Coutts and R. C. Stout. 2004. Effect of Seeding Rate on Alfalfa Stand Longevity. Agron. J. 96:717-722
T Stem densities for the MO94 study (data not presented) were not different among seeding rates at any sampling time. There were 623 stems m–2 13 MAP
T and only 350 stems m–2 by 25 MAP. Stem density remained nearly constant at that level through 49 MAP. During the same time period, plant density
T declined from an average of 100 down to 25 plants m–2. This means that there was a fourfold increase in stems per plant from 25 to 49 MAP during
T the same time period. Thereafter, stem density continued to decline to 290 and 260 stems m–2 at 63 and 73 MAP, respectively, while plant density fell
T below 15 plants m–2 during the same time period. Crowns develop stems in response to light (Cowett and Sprague, 1962) and apparently could not
T continue to maintain high stem density with the thin stand and older plants.
T
T data as shown above.
T MAP = months after planting
T SPM2 = stems per square meter
T PPM2 = plants per square meter
T SPP = stems per plant
